## 3. Dataset Anatomy (Decoding the Matrix)

To process structured data, you must speak the language of a Data Scientist. Let's look at an abstract dataset predicting if a bank will approve a loan.

```text
+-----------+---------+---------------+---------------+----------------+
| Record ID | Age     | Credit_Score  | Income        | Loan_Approved  |
+-----------+---------+---------------+---------------+----------------+
| 001       | 28      | 720           | 55000         | Yes            |
| 002       | 45      | 590           | 42000         | No             |
| 003       | 34      | 810           | 90000         | Yes            |
+-----------+---------+---------------+---------------+----------------+

```

### The Breakdown:

* **Rows (Observations / Records):** A horizontal slice. It represents one single, complete entity. (e.g., Record `001` is one specific applicant).
* **Columns (Variables):** A vertical slice. It represents a specific attribute measured across all entities (e.g., `Credit_Score`).
* **Features (Inputs):** The columns the model uses to make a decision. Here, `Age`, `Credit_Score`, and `Income` are features. These are the clues.
* **Labels (Output):** The exact column the model is actively trying to predict. Here, `Loan_Approved` is the label.

> **💡 Think Like a Product Builder**
> The design of your features dictates the success of your product. If you try to predict Netflix movie preferences (Label) but only feed the model the user's shoe size and hair color (Features), the model will fail entirely. There must be a logical, underlying relationship for the math to discover.

