## 7. Data Leakage (The Silent Killer)

### What it is

Data Leakage occurs when information from *outside* the training dataset is used to create the model. Specifically, it happens when the model is accidentally given access to information it would never have in the real world at the exact moment of prediction.

### Why it is dangerous

Data leakage results in a model that looks like a genius during training (99.9% accuracy) but performs terribly in production (random guessing). It creates a false illusion of success.

### Real-World Example

**Goal:** Predict if a user will default on their credit card next month.
**The Mistake:** The engineer includes a feature column called `Late_Fee_Charged`.
**The Leak:** The bank only charges a late fee *after* the user defaults. During training, the model realizes: "Wow! Every time `Late_Fee_Charged` is True, they default! I am a genius!"
**The Reality:** In production, when trying to predict the *future*, the `Late_Fee_Charged` column will always be blank because the default hasn't happened yet. The model collapses.

> **💡 Think Like a Researcher**
> To prevent data leakage, always ask yourself: *"Will this exact piece of data be available in the production database at the precise millisecond I need to make the prediction?"* If the answer is no, drop the feature.

